	</form></div><span class="pb doctop" title="page number in print edition" id="ADMS-06-16-02-pb-0427">427<a style="padding-left: 5px" onclick="window.open('/img-document-get.xqy?image=ADMS/Pages/ADMS-06-16/ADMS-06-16-02-pb-0427.jpg', 'pageImage', 'scrollbars=1,resizable=1'); return false" onkeypress="this.onclick();" tabindex="0" title="Click to view image of page from print edition"><img src="/img-ML/page-icon.gif" width="18" height="20" style="vertical-align:middle;" alt="page icon"/></a></span><div class="doc">
      
      <h1>From C. W. F. Dumas</h1>
      <div class="docbody">
        <div class="opener">
          <table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		<td class="salutationLeft">Monsieur,</td>
		<td class="salutationRight">Lahaie 12<span class="hi-super" style="font-size: 80%; line-height: 0.8; vertical-align: super;">e.</span> Nov. 1784</td>
	      </tr>
      </table>
        </div>
        <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">Jai reu avec grand plaisir lhonore vtre du 3 Nov. &amp; jai fait dj usage de son contenu &amp; dans une Lettre au Congrs, &amp; auprs de ces Messieurs dAmsterdam.<a class="ptr" href="#ADMS-06-16-02-0244-fn-0001" id="ADMS-06-16-02-0244-fn-0001-ptr">1</a></p>
        <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">Vous recevrez, Monsieur, incessament par le canal indiqu de Mr. C. Storer, <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">the true history of a Madman.</span><a class="ptr" href="#ADMS-06-16-02-0244-fn-0002" id="ADMS-06-16-02-0244-fn-0002-ptr">2</a></p>
        <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">Au mois de 7br. dernier je reus une Lettre de Mr. D. Humphreys, <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Secr<span class="hi-super" style="font-size: 80%; line-height: 0.8; vertical-align: super;">y.</span> to the Commission of the Am<span class="hi-super" style="font-size: 80%; line-height: 0.8; vertical-align: super;">n.</span> Min<span class="hi-super" style="font-size: 80%; line-height: 0.8; vertical-align: super;">rs.</span> Pl.,</span> qui en renfermois une pour M<span class="hi-super" style="font-size: 80%; line-height: 0.8; vertical-align: super;">r.</span> Thulemeyer de leur part, que je remis en main propre, &amp; lui en donnai avis en rponse. Le 8 Octobre jenvoyai au mme Mr. D. Humphreys la rponse ministrielle de Mr. Thulemeyer. Il ne men a point accus la rception. Voici une autre Lettre de Mr. Thulemeyer pour V. E. Il est fort surpris &amp; inquiet de navoir pas de rponse encore  sa prcedente, de la part de lhon<span class="hi-super" style="font-size: 80%; line-height: 0.8; vertical-align: super;">ble.</span> Commission. Jen dois une  Mr. votre fils, qui voudra bien avoir la charit de me faire crdit jusqu la semaine prochaine.<a class="ptr" href="#ADMS-06-16-02-0244-fn-0003" id="ADMS-06-16-02-0244-fn-0003-ptr">3</a> Nous lembrassons cordialement, &amp; le prions de prsenter nos hoeurs  Mesdames Adams. Je suis avec le plus cordial respect, de Votre Excellence / le trs humble &amp; trs obissant / serviteur</p>
        <div class="closer">
          <p class="signed">C.w.f. Dumas</p>
        </div>
        <div class="postscript">
          <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">Linondation des frontieres en lchant toutes les Ecluses, a parfaitement russi.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <span class="pb center" title="page number in print edition" id="ADMS-06-16-02-pb-0428">[428<a style="padding-left: 0px" onclick="window.open('/img-document-get.xqy?image=ADMS/Pages/ADMS-06-16/ADMS-06-16-02-pb-0428.jpg', 'pageImage', 'scrollbars=1,resizable=1'); return false" onkeypress="this.onclick();" tabindex="0" title="Click to view image of page from print edition"><img src="/img-ML/page-icon.gif" width="18" height="20" style="vertical-align:middle;" alt="page icon"/></a>]</span>
      <div class="translation">
        <h2>TRANSLATION</h2>
        <div class="opener">
          <table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		<td class="salutationLeft">Sir</td>
		<td class="salutationRight">The Hague, 12 November 1784</td>
	      </tr>
      </table>
        </div>
        <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">I received with great pleasure your esteemed letter of 3 November, and I have already made use of its contents in a letter to Congress and with those gentlemen from Amsterdam.<a class="ptr" href="#ADMS-06-16-02-0244-fn-0001" id="ADMS-06-16-02-0244-fn-0001-ptr">1</a></p>
        <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">You, sir, will very shortly receive by the designated route of Mr. Charles Storer, <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">the true history of a Madman.</span><a class="ptr" href="#ADMS-06-16-02-0244-fn-0002" id="ADMS-06-16-02-0244-fn-0002-ptr">2</a></p>
        <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">Last September I received a letter from Mr. David Humphreys, <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">secretary to the commission of the American ministers plenipotentiary,</span> enclosing one from them to Mr. Thulemeier. I delivered that letter into Mr. Thulemeiers own hands and relayed his response back to Mr. Humphreys. On 8 October I sent the ministerial response from Mr. Thulemeier to the same Mr. Humphreys. He has not confirmed its receipt at all. Here is another letter from Mr. Thulemeier to your excellency. He is extremely surprised and anxious to have not yet received from the honorable commission a response to his earlier letter. I owe a letter to your son, who would be kind to extend credit to me until next week.<a class="ptr" href="#ADMS-06-16-02-0244-fn-0003" id="ADMS-06-16-02-0244-fn-0003-ptr">3</a> We heartily embrace him and ask him to pay our honors to the Adams ladies. I am with the most cordial respect, your excellencys very humble and very obedient servant</p>
        <div class="closer">
          <p class="signed">C.w.f. Dumas</p>
        </div>
        <div class="postscript">
          <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">The flooding of the borders by opening all the locks has succeeded perfectly.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="docback">
        <div class="note-source" id="ADMS-06-16-02-0244-sn">
          
   <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;"><abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ recipients copy (A recipients copy is assumed to be in the hand of the signer unless it is otherwise described.) ]">RC</abbr> (<span class="ref-terms" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ &lt;expan&gt;Manuscripts and other materials, 16391889, in the Adams Manuscript Trust collection given to the Massachusetts Historical Society in 1956 and enlarged by a few additions of family papers since then. Citations in the present edition are simply by date of the original document if the original is in the main chronological series of the Papers and therefore readily found in the microfilm edition of the Adams Papers (see below).&lt;/expan&gt; ]">Adams Papers</span>); internal address: A Son Excellence Mr. Adams.</p>

        </div>
        <div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#ADMS-06-16-02-0244-fn-0001-ptr" id="ADMS-06-16-02-0244-fn-0001">1</a>
          
   <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">With his <a href="default.xqy?keys=ADMS-print-06-16-02-0238" class="document">3 Nov.</a> letter to Dumas, above, <abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ John Adams (17351826) ]">JA</abbr> enclosed his answers to a series of questions forwarded by Dumas with his 26 Oct. letter, also above. Dumas, in turn, enclosed both questions and answers with his 7 Nov. letter to the president of Congress (<span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ &lt;i&gt;The Diplomatic Correspondence of the United States of America, from  1783, to  1789,&lt;/i&gt; [[ed. William A. Weaver]], repr., Washington, D.C., 1837 [[actually 1855]]; 3 vols. ]"><span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Dipl. Corr., 17831789,</span></span> 3:524526, 529530). For the questions and <abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ John Adams (17351826) ]">JA</abbr>s answers, see his <a href="default.xqy?keys=ADMS-print-06-16-02-0237" class="document">3 Nov.</a> letter to Congress, and <a href="default.xqy?keys=ADMS-print-06-16-02-0237&amp;expandNote=ADMS-06-16-02-0237-fn-0003#ADMS-06-16-02-0237-fn-0003" class="document">note 3</a>, above.</p>

        </div>

        <div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#ADMS-06-16-02-0244-fn-0002-ptr" id="ADMS-06-16-02-0244-fn-0002">2</a>
          
   <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">Probably a reference to Dumas 7 Nov. letter to the president of Congress (<span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ &lt;i&gt;The Diplomatic Correspondence of the United States of America, from  1783, to  1789,&lt;/i&gt; [[ed. William A. Weaver]], repr., Washington, D.C., 1837 [[actually 1855]]; 3 vols. ]"><span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Dipl. Corr., 17831789,</span></span> 3:524526), which opens with a discussion of the character of Joseph II and which appears to have been the letter that Charles Storer received from Dumas and forwarded to <abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ John Adams (17351826) ]">JA</abbr> with his <a href="default.xqy?keys=ADMS-print-06-16-02-0250" class="document">letter of 22 Nov.</a>, below.</p>

        </div>

        <div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#ADMS-06-16-02-0244-fn-0003-ptr" id="ADMS-06-16-02-0244-fn-0003">3</a>
          
   <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;"><abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ John Quincy Adams (17671848), son of John and Abigail Adams ]">JQA</abbr>s letter to Dumas has not been found, but Dumas reply of 25 Nov. (<span class="ref-terms" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ &lt;expan&gt;Manuscripts and other materials, 16391889, in the Adams Manuscript Trust collection given to the Massachusetts Historical Society in 1956 and enlarged by a few additions of family papers since then. Citations in the present edition are simply by date of the original document if the original is in the main chronological series of the Papers and therefore readily found in the microfilm edition of the Adams Papers (see below).&lt;/expan&gt; ]">Adams Papers</span>) indicates that, among other things, <abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ John Quincy Adams (17671848), son of John and Abigail Adams ]">JQA</abbr> had remarked on his reading of classical authors. He also apparently mentioned Beaumarchais <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Le mariage de Figaro,</span> then playing in Paris, on which <abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ John Quincy Adams (17671848), son of John and Abigail Adams ]">JQA</abbr> commented at some length in his 10 Nov. letter to Peter Jay Munro (<span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Museum of the City of New York ]">NNMus</span>).</p>

        </div>

      </div>
